08137nam a22011055i 9783110679632DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020948239  a97831106796327 a10.1515/97831106796322doi  a(DE-B1597)537183  a(OCoLC)1226679290  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aNX160b.C67 2021 4aNX160b.C67 2021 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a701/.9223  aAP 11500qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/6852:00aConstructions of Media Authorship :bInvestigating Aesthetic Practices from Early Modernity to the Digital Age /ced. by Christiane Heibach, Angela Krewani, Irene Schütze. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VI, 268 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tConstructions of Media Authorship: Investigating Aesthetic Practices from Early Modernity to the Digital Age – An Introduction -- tAssigning Authorship to Artistic Practices -- tNaming and Not-Naming: Authorial Gestures in Contemporary Art -- tBauhaus – A Trademark without Author? Remarks on Authorship in Design -- tAuthorship in the Contemporary Production of Metal Sculptures: Art Theory, Technology, Law and the Organization of Work -- tThe Artist, the Author and Authenticity -- tIs Copyright Law the Zombie of Authorship? -- tAvant-Gardes Practices and the Erosion of Authorship -- tHave We Ever Been Modern? Reflections on Some Myths of Literary Production -- tAutopoietic Processes within the Avant-Gardes: Fragmenting Authorship -- tGendered Discourses on Authorship in Film and Video -- tCollaborative Authorship – Or How to Overcome the “Nightmare of Participation” -- tDispersed Authorship in Contemporary Media -- tThe Camera-stylo of Postfeminist Auteurism: Sofia Coppola’s “Cinema of Relief” -- tAuteurism and Anonymity in Television: On the Domestication and Dispersion of Television Authorship -- tHacks as Means of Meaning-making -- tClaiming Authorship? Machinima Production and the Streaming Practices of Gamers -- tAuthors, Fans, Pirates: On Fan Practices and Authorship -- tPsychic Residues or: Maths, Wires, Code -- tImages: Credits, Copyrights and Sources -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe author is dead, long live the author! This paradox has shaped discussions on authorship since at least the 1960s, when the dominant notion of the individual author-genius was first critically questioned. The ongoing discussion has mainly focused on literature and the arts, but has ignored nearly any artistic practice beyond these two fields. “Constructions of Media Authorship” aims to fill this gap: the volume’s interdisciplinary contributions reflect historical and current artistic practices within various media and attempt to grasp them from different perspectives.The first part sheds a new light on different artistic and design practices and questions the still dominant view on the individual identifiable author. The second part discusses creative practices in literature, emphasizing the interrelation of aesthetic discourses and media practices. The third part investigates authoring in audiovisual media, especially film and TV, while the final part turns to electronic and digital media and their collective creativity and hybrid mediality. The volume is also an attempt to develop new methodological approaches, focusing on the interplay between various human and non-human actors in different media constellations.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aArtsxHistory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aAuthorship.  acreative/artistic practices.  adigital media.1 aBruder, Johannes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go